{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639230"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17766"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17766"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62407"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24462"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common form of dementia is Alzheimer\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the pathophysiology of Alzheimer\u0027s disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune destruction of acetylcholine receptors","Degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra","Inflammation and demyelination of peripheral nerves","Demyelination of neurons in the central nervous system","Accumulation of amyloid-beta plaques and tau tangles in the brain"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of amyloid-beta plaques and tau tangles in the brain\u003C/strong\u003E is the hallmark of Alzheimer\u0027s disease. These pathological changes lead to neurodegeneration and are associated with the progressive cognitive decline seen in affected individuals. The hippocampus, a region critical for memory, is one of the first areas affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDemyelination of neurons in the central nervous system\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of multiple sclerosis, not Alzheimer\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction of acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the pathophysiological mechanism in myasthenia gravis, a condition affecting neuromuscular transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with Parkinson\u0027s disease, leading to motor symptoms such as tremor and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammation and demyelination of peripheral nerves\u003C/strong\u003E are features of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome, which presents with acute flaccid paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alzheimer\u0027s disease is characterised by the accumulation of amyloid-beta plaques and tau tangles in the brain.","Neurodegeneration in Alzheimer\u0027s disease leads to progressive cognitive decline.","The hippocampus is one of the first regions affected in Alzheimer\u0027s disease, leading to memory impairment."],"references":["Imbimbo BP, Lombard J, Pomara N. Pathophysiology of Alzheimer\u0027s disease. Neuroimaging Clin N Am. 2005 Nov;15(4):727-53, ix. doi: 10.1016/j.nic.2005.09.009. PMID: 16443487.","Yarns BC, Holiday KA, Carlson DM, Cosgrove CK, Melrose RJ. Pathophysiology of Alzheimer\u0027s Disease. Psychiatr Clin North Am. 2022 Dec;45(4):663-676. doi: 10.1016/j.psc.2022.07.003. Epub 2022 Oct 14. PMID: 36396271.","Tiwari S, Atluri V, Kaushik A, Yndart A, Nair M. Alzheimer\u0027s disease: pathogenesis, diagnostics, and therapeutics. Int J Nanomedicine. 2019 Jul 19;14:5541-5554. doi: 10.2147/IJN.S200490. PMID: 31410002; PMCID: PMC6650620."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62407"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17766"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62407"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:09:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T20:09:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10480"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attrib